commit_message:
Fix slow SG api calls when limiting fields

Relating to the issue with creating rules, when reading security
groups, it is very slow. Even when limiting to id/name, it pulls
in all rules before returning just id/name.

This change looks at the fields requested, and if no "synthetic"
fields are in the list, skips initializing those.

Co-Authored-By: Hongbin Lu<hongbin.lu@huawei.com>
Closes-Bug: #1810563
Change-Id: Id6870633e3943666e9b7fb900ad2d0894ee2715d

commit_message:
OVS agent: always send start flag during initial sync

In order to avoid inaccurate agent_boot_time setting,
this patch suggests to consider agent as "started" only
after completion of initial sync with server.

Change-Id: Icba05288889219e8a606c3809efd88b2c234bef3
Closes-Bug: #1799178
(cherry picked from commit 8f20963c5b9e6762b6322f686bce99871bec6be9)

commit_message:
Re-propose volume backed server rebuild

The spec for support rebuild volume backed
server was accepted in Stein, but some of
the work did not finish, so repropose it
for Train.

Co-Authored-By: ramboman <lijie@unitedstack.com>
blueprint volume-backed-server-rebuild

Previously-approved: Stein

Change-Id: Iadb1898af2eb8ce5ecf0984dea7de729d982b29a
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/nova-specs refs/changes/82/650582/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: .. This work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 3.0 Unported License. http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/legalcode ========================================== volume-backed server rebuild ========================================== https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/volume-backed-server-rebuild Currently, the compute API will `fail`_ if a user tries to rebuild a volume-backed server with a new image. This spec proposes to add support for rebuilding a volume-backed server with a new image. .. _fail: https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/62245235b/nova/compute/api.py#L3318 Problem description =================== Currently Nova rebuild (with a new image) only supports instances which are booted from images. The volume-backed instance cannot be rebuilt when a new image is supplied. Trying to rebuild a volume-backed instance will raise a HTTPBadRequest exception. Use Cases --------- * As a user, I would like to rebuild my volume-backed server with a new image. * As a nova developer, I would like to have feature parity in the compute API for volume-backed and image-backed servers. Proposed change =============== First, change the existing API for rebuilding a volume-backed server. Then the API flow would be: #. Has the new API microversion been requested? #. Is the instance.host service version new enough to support volume-backed rebuild with a new image? If these are true, proceed. If not, fail in the API with a 409 error. Note that when rebuilding with a new image, the request will be run through the scheduler against the current host to be consistent with image-backed rebuild with a new image. See `bug 1664931`_ for details. .. _bug 1664931: https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1664931 Then the nova-compute will perform the following steps: #. Create an empty (no connector) volume attachment for the volume and server. This ensures the volume remains ``reserved`` through the next step. #. Delete the existing volume attachment (the old one). #. Call the new ``os-reimage`` cinder API. #. Poll the volume status for completion (either success or failure). #. Upon successful completion of the re-image operation, update the empty volume attchment in Cinder, and then do the attachment on the Nova host when spawning the (rebuilt) guest VM and "complete" the attachment which will make the volume ``in-use`` again. In this process, there are some conditions that we could hit: * If we failed to re-image the volume and the volume is in 'error' status then we should set the instance status as "error". Since users can rebuild instances in error status, the user has a way to retry the rebuild once the cause of the cinder side failure is resolved. Note that nova-compute will *not* attempt to update the volume attachment records with the host connector again on the volume in error status. * If the cinder API itself returns a >=400 error, nothing changed about the root volume and in that case the migration status can be 'failed' but the instance status should go back to what it was (we can see how _error_out_instance_on_exception is used). Alternatives ------------ The main alternative is that nova would perform the rebuild like an initial boot from volume where nova-compute would create a new volume from the new image and then "swap" the root volume on the instance during rebuild. There are issues with this, however, like what to do about the old volume: * Regarding 'delete_on_termination' flag in the BDM, delete_on_termination=True means: don't delete the volume when we kill the instance. Rebuild means: re-initialize this instance in place. The rebuild flow would have to determine what to do if the old root volume BDM was marked with delete_on_termination=True - ignore that and preserve the old root volume or delete it. * We could pass a new flag to the rebuild API telling nova what to do about the old volume (delete it or not). If the flag is true to delete the old volume but the old volume has snapshots, Nova won't be deleting the volume snapshots just to delete the volume during a rebuild. But there are several issues with that as mentioned above like quota and the questions about what nova should do about the old volume, you can see more detailed information in `References`_. Data model impact ----------------- None REST API impact --------------- Change the rebuild request response code from 400 to 202 if the conditions described in the `Proposed change`_ section are met. The API microversion and compute RPC version will also be incremented to indicate the new support. Security impact --------------- None Notifications impact -------------------- None Other end user impact --------------------- The python-novaclient and python-openstackclient will be updated to support the new microversion. Performance Impact ------------------ The operation will take longer because of the orchestration involved and the work that needs to happen in Cinder. Other deployer impact --------------------- If the cinder volume ``reimage`` API operation fails and the volume goes to ``error`` status, an admin will likely need to investigate and resolve the issue in cinder and then reset the volume status to ``reserved``. Developer impact ---------------- None Upgrade impact -------------- The API microversion and compute RPC version will also be incremented to indicate the new support, therefore users will not be able to leverage the feature until the nova-compute service hosting a volume-backed instance is upgraded. Implementation ============== Assignee(s) ----------- Primary assignee: Jie Li <lijie@unitedstack.com> (ramboman) Other contributors: Kevin Zheng <zhengzhenyu@huawei.com> Work Items ---------- * Change the existing rebuild API. * Create an empty attachment for the root volume so the volume remains in-use during rebuild (we do this today already). * Delete the old volume attachment. * Call the cinder API to re-image the volume. * Update and complete the volume attachment once re-imaged. * Adopt the new compute version. * Adopt the new microversion in python-novaclient. * Adopt the new microversion in python-openstackclient. * Change the nova API documents. Dependencies ============ Depends on the cinder blueprint for re-imaging a volume, see more detail information in References. Testing ======= The following tests are added. * Nova unit tests for negative scenarios * Nova functional tests for "happy path" testing * Tempest integration tests to make sure the nova/cinder integration works properly Documentation Impact ==================== We will replace the `note in the API reference`_ with a note about the required minimum microversion for rebuilding a volume-backed server with a new image. The following document will be updated: * API Reference .. _note in the API reference: https://developer.openstack.org/api-ref/compute/?expanded=#rebuild-server-rebuild-action References ========== * Stein PTG etherpad: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/nova-ptg-stein * This is the discussion about rebuild the volume-backed server: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-October/123255.html * This is the discussion about what we should do about the root volume during a rebuild: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-operators/2018-March/014952.html * The cinder blueprint for re-imaging a volume: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/cinder/+spec/add-volume-re-image-api History ======= .. list-table:: Revisions :header-rows: 1 * - Release Name - Description * - Stein - Proposed. * - Train - Re-proposed.

commit_message:
ipmi: Ignore sensor debug data

When the conductor has debugging enabled, that command is
passed to ipmitool to enable debugging of other commands.

However, this means tons of extra data is dumped as part of
the sensor data collection for ironic, which breaks string
parsing and ultimately metrics collection.

Since we can identify these lines, lets ignore them.

Change-Id: Ife77707210f8289d8f2e0223fb9ee1909d798546
Story: 2005332
Task: 30267
(cherry picked from commit 418a5668a4c947326f28cf13e962e914ebadc012)
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/ironic refs/changes/10/650110/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: def test__parse_ipmi_sensor_data_debug(self): fake_sensors_data = """ << Message tag : 0x00 << RMCP+ status : no errors << Maximum privilege level : admin << Console Session ID : 0xa0a2a3a4 << BMC Session ID : 0x02006a01 << Negotiated authenticatin algorithm : hmac_sha1 << Negotiated integrity algorithm : hmac_sha1_96 << Negotiated encryption algorithm : aes_cbc_128 Sensor ID : Temp (0x2) Entity ID : 3.2 (Processor) Sensor Type (Analog) : Temperature Sensor Reading : 50 (+/- 1) degrees C Status : ok Nominal Reading : 50.000 Normal Minimum : 11.000 Normal Maximum : 69.000 Upper critical : 90.000 Upper non-critical : 85.000 Positive Hysteresis : 1.000 Negative Hysteresis : 1.000 Sensor ID : FAN MOD 1A RPM (0x30) Entity ID : 7.1 (System Board) Sensor Type (Analog) : Fan Sensor Reading : 8400 (+/- 75) RPM Status : ok Nominal Reading : 5325.000 Normal Minimum : 10425.000 Normal Maximum : 14775.000 Lower critical : 4275.000 Positive Hysteresis : 375.000 Negative Hysteresis : 375.000 """ expected_return = { 'Fan': { 'FAN MOD 1A RPM (0x30)': { 'Status': 'ok', 'Sensor Reading': '8400 (+/- 75) RPM', 'Entity ID': '7.1 (System Board)', 'Normal Minimum': '10425.000', 'Positive Hysteresis': '375.000', 'Normal Maximum': '14775.000', 'Sensor Type (Analog)': 'Fan', 'Lower critical': '4275.000', 'Negative Hysteresis': '375.000', 'Sensor ID': 'FAN MOD 1A RPM (0x30)', 'Nominal Reading': '5325.000' } }, 'Temperature': { 'Temp (0x2)': { 'Status': 'ok', 'Sensor Reading': '50 (+/- 1) degrees C', 'Entity ID': '3.2 (Processor)', 'Normal Minimum': '11.000', 'Positive Hysteresis': '1.000', 'Upper non-critical': '85.000', 'Normal Maximum': '69.000', 'Sensor Type (Analog)': 'Temperature', 'Negative Hysteresis': '1.000', 'Upper critical': '90.000', 'Sensor ID': 'Temp (0x2)', 'Nominal Reading': '50.000' } } } ret = ipmi._parse_ipmi_sensors_data(self.node, fake_sensors_data) self.assertEqual(expected_return, ret)

commit_message:
Use full branch name as build_image.sh argument

`build_image.sh` expects full branch name as argument like e.g.
`stable/stein`. This change fixes Zuul playbook to pass the right
argument.

Change-Id: Ie132389a21ed74cec4e7e22ecdcb9254964b9d3c

added_lines: self._add_delete_template() def test_template_dont_show_deleted_template(self): uuid = self._add_delete_template() # 'show template' and check for an empty output response = utils.run_vitrage_command('vitrage template show ' + uuid) self.assertEqual("", response, message="Shouldn't show a DELETED template") # Expected: an empty string. def _add_delete_template(self): """ A helper function: Adds and deletes a template. Returns its uuid. """ # add a template v_utils.add_template(STANDARD_TEMPLATE, template_type=TTypes.STANDARD) db_row = v_utils.get_first_template(name='host_high_memory_usage_scenarios', type=TTypes.STANDARD, status=TemplateStatus.ACTIVE) self.assertIsNotNone(db_row, 'Template should appear in templates list') # delete it uuid = db_row['uuid'] v_utils.delete_template(uuid) db_row = v_utils.get_first_template(name='host_high_memory_usage_scenarios', type=TTypes.STANDARD) self.assertIsNone(db_row, 'Template should not appear in list') return uuid
deleted_lines: # add standard template v_utils.add_template(STANDARD_TEMPLATE, template_type=TTypes.STANDARD) db_row = v_utils.get_first_template( name='host_high_memory_usage_scenarios', type=TTypes.STANDARD, status=TemplateStatus.ACTIVE) self.assertIsNotNone(db_row, 'Template should appear in templates list') # delete template uuid = db_row['uuid'] v_utils.delete_template(uuid) db_row = v_utils.get_first_template( name='host_high_memory_usage_scenarios', type=TTypes.STANDARD) self.assertIsNone(db_row, 'Template should not appear in list')

subject: Fix amp failover where failover already failed
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2018-03-01 16:22:34.000000000', 'files': [], 'web_link': 'https://opendev.org/openstack/octavia/commit/2c2e954c654ad71cc82b28af6ebe3e1bf61b4af6', 'message': 'Fix amp failover where failover already failed

If a failover ran on an amphora and was unsuccessful and reverted, it
would mark the amp status "DELETED" and un-busy the health record.
It would then be picked up on the next failover check, start failing
over, and break early since it appeared to be "unallocated".

Also, housekeeping can now clean up expired amphora records based on the
amphora's updated_at time instead of the health record's time, which
means the records won't be immediately cleaned up anymore after they go
through failover flows.

Change-Id: I848b7fc69b977fcb39f8a07e2ea5fc7bd37b5c7a

commit_message:
Fix amp failover where failover already failed

If a failover ran on an amphora and was unsuccessful and reverted, it
would mark the amp status "DELETED" and un-busy the health record.
It would then be picked up on the next failover check, start failing
over, and break early since it appeared to be "unallocated".

Also, housekeeping can now clean up expired amphora records based on the
amphora's updated_at time instead of the health record's time, which
means the records won't be immediately cleaned up anymore after they go
through failover flows.

Change-Id: I848b7fc69b977fcb39f8a07e2ea5fc7bd37b5c7a

commit_message:
Update UPPER_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/stein

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/stein branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: I9845abdd6577267e2f3abaf1f57cf8731a66c733

commit_message:
Use full branch name as build_image.sh argument

`build_image.sh` expects full branch name as argument like e.g.
`stable/stein`. This change fixes Zuul playbook to pass the right
argument.

Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/649538

commit_message:
Add config template changes to support Ironic

Add changes specifically to support the Pike release of Ironic,
which introduced a new type of config option for the driver support
matrix.

Reference:
https://docs.openstack.org/ironic/pike/install/enabling-drivers.html

Change-Id: I5286aa4b71b72e5477b4d58e0347de446f4a7dac

commit_message:
Remove checking m1.tiny flavor

Instead of checking whether m1.tiny flavor exists simply
create the default flavors and ignore errors if a flavor
already exists.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I573b90b354b93ebf81eaa4f5df0a614a9b99a24b

commit_message:
Fix Ansible WARNING logs on reserved name: action

When using kolla-ansible the following log is always display:

[WARNING]: Found variable using reserved name: action

As describe in https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/2.3/playbooks_directives.html
"action" keywork is reserved for Task.

Hence playbook input variable named 'action' is replaced by 'method'.

Closes-Bug: #1724854
Change-Id: I7afc3d7d80a55ef9dc05f97f9f04e81e5b588be1

commit_message:
Cannot deploy controller without tunnel_interface

It looks like all.yml variables are evaluated before going into
templates and therefore we cannot skip them with template's
if-endif blocks. tunnel_interface_address is set in all.yml and
is evaluated for ml2_conf.ini.j2 before we parse the template and
decide whether it is needed on controllers or not.

Change-Id: Ia936ebb11485dd2c695dcb27bd1600b2a2801e13
Closes-Bug: #1723124

Turn off galera in aio

For devmode, if you just shutdown aio (turn of laptop for example),
galera will still assume full shutdown and you'll have to go through
manual steps to restart it.

commit_message:
Fix the task about --limit does not perform

This task "Gather facts for all hosts (if using --limit)" is not
executed when the --limit parameter is added. Need to add
"tag: always" to solve this bug.
Closes-bug: #1711266

Change-Id: I4cda0454e1172518a372ebb91875ad437dc64c0c

commit_message:
Use ansible fact for interface containing dash

tunnel_interface_address is not assigned in case that
tunnel_interface name contain dash.
Ansible facts name do not match interface name containing dash.
Ansible fact name is generated from interface name where all
dashes are replaced with underscores.

Current fix replace dashes in interface name with underscore
before searching for coresponding ansibe fact

Change-Id: I798cad75ada1bed763a4504d0ca5a4bfd315c2e9
Closes-Bug: #1711757

commit_message:
Add OSIC Scale Testing Documentation

The expectation here is that folks working on the OSIC scale
testing will collaborate on this document and edit it as they
finish up the work they volunteered for.  Once the work is
finished and the four weeks have elapsed, we will publish this
via the normal docs.oo website.

Co-Authored-By: Paul Bourke <paul.bourke@oracle.com>
Co-Authored-By: Swapnil Kulkarni (coolsvap) <me@coolsvap.net>
Co-Authored-By: Jeffrey Zhang <zhang.lei.fly@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I9f7a883a93e6a4e3f17479bd1529aaf72e5b9c2d

added_lines: .. Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License"); you may not use this file except in compliance with the License. You may obtain a copy of the License at http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0 Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS, WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied. See the License for the specific language governing permissions and limitations under the License. ================== OSIC Scale Testing ================== Overview ======== The OpenStack Innovation Center loaned the Kolla community 131 machines from August 3rd, 2016 for a period of four weeks. This documentation details our efforts to scale test Kolla and provide real benchmark numbers to assist Operators in making an operational deployment management (ODM) choice. Benchmarking Overview ===================== The first purpose of these benchmarks is to allow the community to compare their bare-metal servers with the servers used during Kolla scale testing. The second purpose is to objectively show the performance ofthe servers under test. Ultimately the Kolla community recommends evaluating Kolla completely before making any operational deployment manager (ODM) choice. That evaluation may include scale and performance, to determine if Kolla meets the performance requirements you, the Operator, may have. There is significant data in this documentation. The purpose of the data is to ensure the results are reproducible by others if making an equivalent comparison. Overvoew of Servers under Test ============================== 131 identical servers Model: HP DL380 Gen9 Processor: 2x 12-core Intel E5-2680 v3 @ 2.50GHz RAM: 256GB (24 of HP brand 2133 MHz Registered ECC Rank 2 16384 MB DIMMS) Storage: 12x 800GB Intel S3500 SSD in RAID10 or 12x 800GB Intel S3700 SSD in RAID10 NICs: 2x Intel X710 Dual Port 10 GbE Note: The details of the characterization should go in a separate document but lets keep it all together for the moment to make collaborating on the review simpler and split it out before we merge the documentation. Characteriziations of major subsystems of servers under test ============================================================ CPU Characterization -------------------- The Kolla Community used the sysbench tool to produce a CPU benchmark. This tool works by calculating prime numbers. In the included execution report, prime numbers up to 200000 were calculated across 24 cores. :: root@729494-comp-s3500-002:~/Linux# sysbench --test=cpu --num-threads=24 --cpu-max-prime=200000 run sysbench 0.4.12: multi-threaded system evaluation benchmark Running the test with following options: Number of threads: 24 Doing CPU performance benchmark Threads started! Done. Maximum prime number checked in CPU test: 200000 Test execution summary: total time: 29.0205s total number of events: 10000 total time taken by event execution: 695.4614 per-request statistics: min: 66.33ms avg: 69.55ms max: 96.84ms approx. 95 percentile: 81.73ms Threads fairness: events (avg/stddev): 416.6667/0.90 execution time (avg/stddev): 28.9776/0.02 RAM Characteriziation --------------------- The Kolla Community used the Intel Memory Latency Checker v3.1a to obtain a report of the Memory bandwidth and latency. While this tool is closed-source, it functions well with Intel Xeon processors and produces a wealth of information related to the performance of the memory subsystem and chipset. THe exact output from the tool: :: root@729494-comp-s3500-002:~/Linux# ./mlc_avx512 Intel(R) Memory Latency Checker - v3.1a Measuring idle latencies (in ns)... Numa node Numa node 0 1 0 91.4 125.5 1 125.3 91.1 Measuring Peak Memory Bandwidths for the system Bandwidths are in MB/sec (1 MB/sec = 1,000,000 Bytes/sec) Using all the threads from each core if Hyper-threading is enabled Using traffic with the following read-write ratios ALL Reads : 121964.7 3:1 Reads-Writes : 116514.9 2:1 Reads-Writes : 115049.8 1:1 Reads-Writes : 102771.1 Stream-triad like: 109336.4 Measuring Memory Bandwidths between nodes within system Bandwidths are in MB/sec (1 MB/sec = 1,000,000 Bytes/sec) Using all the threads from each core if Hyper-threading is enabled Using Read-only traffic type Numa node Numa node 0 1 0 57845.1 28962.8 1 28871.1 57419.3 Measuring Loaded Latencies for the system Using all the threads from each core if Hyper-threading is enabled Using Read-only traffic type Inject Latency Bandwidth Delay (ns) MB/sec ========================== 00000 222.53 121408.3 00002 222.72 121525.2 00008 223.32 121663.8 00015 223.02 121863.0 00050 220.39 122181.7 00100 195.38 121052.9 00200 111.56 79365.2 00300 103.18 53999.9 00400 99.62 41155.2 00500 97.53 33405.6 00700 96.15 24308.7 01000 94.80 17340.2 01300 94.14 13560.3 01700 93.78 10556.4 02500 93.47 7411.1 03500 93.34 5498.2 05000 93.01 4064.4 09000 93.00 2562.5 20000 92.57 1537.5 Measuring cache-to-cache transfer latency (in ns)... Local Socket L2->L2 HIT latency 33.8 Local Socket L2->L2 HITM latency 38.1 Remote Socket LLC->LLC HITM latency (data address homed in writer socket) Reader Numa Node Writer Numa Node 0 1 0 - 81.0 1 81.3 - Remote Socket LLC->LLC HITM latency (data address homed in reader socket) Reader Numa Node Writer Numa Node 0 1 0 - 80.1 1 81.5 - Storage Characterization ------------------------ The Kolla community used the bonnie++ benchmarking tool to characterize the disk file performance. We used a filesize of 520GB as bonnie++ operates correctly only when the file size is double the system RAM. The exact output from the tool: :: root@729494-comp-s3500-002:/openstack# bonnie++ -d /var/lib/nova -s 520G -n 0 -m TEST -f -b -u root Using uid:0, gid:0. Writing intelligently...done Rewriting...done Reading intelligently...done start 'em...done...done...done...done...done... Version 1.97 ------Sequential Output------ --Sequential Input- --Random- Concurrency 1 -Per Chr- --Block-- -Rewrite- -Per Chr- --Block-- --Seeks-- Machine Size K/sec %CP K/sec %CP K/sec %CP K/sec %CP K/sec %CP /sec %CP TEST 520G 1290982 95 333113 33 537217 30 318.3 98 Latency 325ms 4906ms 7290us 2981us NIC Characterization -------------------- Not sure how to characterize the NIC performance - need some help here System Configuration ==================== Ubuntu 14.04.3 LTS Trustry Tahr Kernel information: Linux 729494-comp-s3500-002 4.4.0-31-generic #50~14.04.1-Ubuntu SMP Wed Jul 13 01:07:32 UTC 2016 x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 GNU/Linux Docker version 1.12.0, build 8eab29e Docker Registry version 2 Docker graph driver: aufs Docker Information ================== :: root@729494-comp-s3500-002:/etc/docker# docker info Containers: 1 Running: 1 Paused: 0 Stopped: 0 Images: 195 Server Version: 1.12.0 Storage Driver: aufs Root Dir: /var/lib/docker/aufs Backing Filesystem: extfs Dirs: 141 Dirperm1 Supported: true Logging Driver: json-file Cgroup Driver: cgroupfs Plugins: Volume: local Network: null overlay host bridge Swarm: inactive Runtimes: runc Default Runtime: runc Security Options: apparmor Kernel Version: 4.4.0-31-generic Operating System: Ubuntu 14.04.3 LTS OSType: linux Architecture: x86_64 CPUs: 48 Total Memory: 251.8 GiB Name: 729494-comp-s3500-002 ID: RPOX:INEX:FCUQ:A3WQ:BGRG:ULTP:P47P:R3NF:PQEL:JYT3:FDEJ:N3U2 Docker Root Dir: /var/lib/docker Debug Mode (client): false Debug Mode (server): false Registry: https://index.docker.io/v1/ WARNING: No swap limit support Insecure Registries: 172.21.0.253:5000 127.0.0.0/8 Scale Scenario #1 ================= In this scenario the Kolla community tested Kolla with out of the box defaults. It was necessary to change a few configuration options related to making Kolla work in a baic way as described in the quickstart guide. The inventory file was configured as follows: 4 control nodes 101 compute nodes 0 storage nodes The results of this test scenario were that Kolla was able to deploy OpenStack in 20 minutes (a cut and paste of the time command results is needed here), and the OpenStack deployment was able to create virtual machines via Nova that had full connectivity to the network. Scale Scenario #1 worked correctly without any code modification and was successful. LINK TO YouTube VIDEO GOES HERE Scale Scenario #2 ================= Follow same style as Scenario #1. Scale Scenario #3 ================= Follow same style s Scenario #2.

engines, let's move them to Kolla.

commit_message:
Proposal spec for universal containers

This is a meta specification to discuss potential direction for Kolla to
provide universal deployment tool agnostic OpenStack containers in a
standarized way as a separate artifact.

Change-Id: I18b319cb796192a1e61ecd516a485dc82d52652f
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/kolla refs/changes/75/330575/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: .. This work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 3.0 Unported License. http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/legalcode ============================================================= Universal deployment tool agnostic OpenStack containerization ============================================================= https://blueprints.launchpad.net/kolla/+spec/universal-containers This is a meta specification to discuss potential direction for Kolla to provide universal deployment tool agnostic OpenStack containers in a standarized way as a separate artifact. Problem description =================== There are different deployment tools that are already consuming containers for OpenStack installation: * Kolla-Ansible * Kolla-K8s * Kolla-Mesos (abandoned, but still good example) and that others that could potentially use them as an option: * Puppet * Fuel * Chef * and etc. Due to the number of potential consumers of OpenStack containers it'll be great to have a single approach for containerizing all OpenStack services and have a CI pipeline that will produce well tested images and publish them to make different deployment tools be able to re-use the same containers. The main benefit is that there will be huge community working on the same set of the container images and consuming them in different deployments that will provide great feedback. Use cases --------- 1. Provide reusable universal containers with standarized characteristics, layers, versions, paths and etc. to make any deployment tool be able to consume them. 2. CI pipeline that will build, test and publish containers for supported stable and master branches with minimal latency to be consumed by different deployment tools. Proposed change =============== This section consists of the list of proposed key characteristics (use cases for the deployment tools) needed to implement universal OpenStack containers. Separate containers definitions and deployment tools ---------------------------------------------------- We should separate Docker container definitions from Ansible deployment code. We should not mix "packaging" of OpenStack services with one of the possible deployment tools that will be consuming them. From a technical point of view - it's the only way to implement separate core teams and releasing model for the deployment tool that will not affect lifecycle of the OpenStack containerization. From implementation point of view it means we should move all Ansible related code and wrappers to a separate repository. One Repository per OpenStack component -------------------------------------- Split Docker container definitions the same way as it is done for Puppet and Ansible - single repository per OpenStack service. It'll allow to use more precise versioning schema of container image manifests and enable more intelligent testing and maintenance as we will have ability to have specific jobs and separate core subteams for different repositories. Due to the fact that there will be huge umber or repositories (few dozens), the preferred way of their definition is to use some DSL. It'll allow managing same standartized way of the images defintion across all repositories and implemented validation. Avoid bootstrap code in containers ---------------------------------- Move bootstrapping scripts from the container itself to the deployment tool. There are different options for implementing it - could be done using the entry point script that will fetch needed boostrap scripts (and probably config files) to the container and execute them or using the native features of the deployment tools like ConfigMap in Kubernetes. Unified paths and endpoints ---------------------------- Unify and document paths and way how the OpenStack services will be executed on different base OSes and installation types. It's needed to ensure that all deployment tools will be able to rely on the contract provided by Kolla and don't depend on base OS or installation type. Additionally, it'll simplify consumption of images from different sources such as builds from custom sources and etc. CI pipeline ----------- CI should act as a pipeline that produces well tested container images with the OpenStack services for all supported stable branches and current master. All published containers should be never overriden to allow deployment tools implement continuously upgradable clouds. In that case "well tested" means that there should be OpenStack deployment jobs running some functional tests and OpenStack components tests to ensure that OpenStack is up and running well. Tempest tests with filters based on the set of deployed OpenStack services could be used as the main tool for container images verification. Security impact --------------- No changes. In general it should simplify audit of the containers securite because of the separation to different repositories and extraction of additional software (such as Ansible) and bootstrap scripts. Performance Impact ------------------ It probably impacts performance of the "build all images" tool that will need to clone dozens of git repositories first. Deployment itself will not be affected. Alternatives ------------ Keep everything as is. The most clear negative side of the proposal is that it will require testing images with different deplyment tools and make any changes to image much more difficult to make. Implementation ============== Assignee(s) ----------- It's kind of meta spec to discuss proposed direction. I think it doesn't require assignees, milestones and work items so far because of the wide potential scope. If direction will be accepted, I'd like to propose covering corresponding areas with separated specific specs. Milestones ---------- TBD later. Work Items ---------- TBD later. Testing ======= In general it'll require additional coverage in terms of testing and few deployment tools to be used for testing in gate. Documentation Impact ==================== Documentation will need significant updates and it'll be needed to make separation between main "framework" repo, per-component repos with containers definitions (if needed) and Ansible deployment tool. References ========== * `Ansible repos <https://github.com/openstack/?utf8=&query=ansible>`_ * `Puppet repos <https://github.com/openstack/?utf8=&query=puppet>`_ * `Kubernetes ConfigMap <http://kubernetes.io/docs/user-guide/configmap/>`_

commit_message:
Expose the ARGS parameter in the start.sh

Currently, we mask the ARGS parameter in a way, that it can only
be set inside the image via the extended start script. Thus the
prominent way to change this ARGS is to re-build the image.
This change, now exposes the ARGS parameter to take its default
value from the environment variable ARGS. Thus giving us option
to set the value from ansible. Howeever, setting the value from
inside the image will take precedence over the environment
variable.

Change-Id: Ifed17a56f54c874c316630a3f245a85dcc5abba0

commit_message:
Use recommended twine check for README validation

The use of ``python setup.py check -r -s`` is actually deprecated and
the recommended method for validating a README for PyPi upload is to
build the sdist and wheel and run ``twine check $DIST_PATH``. This
switches our validation check to use the supported method.

Change-Id: I321b8cf6f1e2116d2fe23059d5f13aa6f2ae8b4c
Signed-off-by: Sean McGinnis <sean.mcginnis@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Extend default datasources settings

Add ability to configure such datasources like:
* static (VITRAGE_USE_STATIC)
* doctor (VITRAGE_USE_DOCTOR)
* prometheus (VITRAGE_USE_PROMETHEUS)

All these datasources are disabled now by default.

Change-Id: I60b2810defbd5d2ce63a6408ed5a835efd7c6904

commit_message:
Build docker images in Zuul

Add dummy script `build_image.sh` in docker top folder for building both
depended images to avoid adding special case in Zuul build job.

Small fixes to docker README.

commit_message:
FWaaS v1->v2 DB migration

FWaaS V1 was deleted in Stein.
This patch cherry picks the V1->V2 migration to Rocky, as it make sense to allow users
to migrate before the upgrade.

Run this tool using: neutron-fwaas-migrate-v1-to-v2 --neutron-db-connection=<neutron database connection string>

Change-Id: I663c173a594137056c96ad4c4b60e810059fb6fa

commit_message:
Use "push" flag for buildah

The push=False flag with use with kolla-build.conf is not working if we
use buildah, clear example is the
tripleo-build-containers-centos-7-buildah job, it's suppose to work like
docker one but it's pushing too.

Closes-Bug: #1822752

Change-Id: I01788b3c11ac701b2cf8c151f95ccad7046532de

commit_message:
[k8s] Set traefik to stable version v1.7.9

The current magnum traefik deployment will always pull latest traefik
container image. With the new launch of traefik v2
(https://blog.containo.us/back-to-traefik-2-0-2f9aa17be305) this will
have impact on how the ingress is described in k8s.

This patch:
* Sets the traefik version to default tag v1.7.9, stable release
prior to v2.
* Adds a new label <ingress_controller_tag> to enable the user
to specify other than default currently in use ingress controller
container release.

Task: 30143
Task: 30146
Story: 2005286

Change-Id: I98cce01d2eca8525875894426d45d365b2ecc7db
Signed-off-by: Diogo Guerra <dy090.guerra@gmail.com>

commit_message:
[k8s] Set traefik to stable version v1.7.9

The current magnum traefik deployment will always pull latest traefik
container image. With the new launch of traefik v2
(https://blog.containo.us/back-to-traefik-2-0-2f9aa17be305) this will
have impact on how the ingress is described in k8s.

This patch:
* Sets the traefik version to default tag v1.7.9, stable release
prior to v2.
* Adds a new label <ingress_controller_tag> to enable the user
to specify other than default currently in use ingress controller
container release.

Task: 30143
Task: 30146
Story: 2005286

Change-Id: I1034e76f1d0619183dfa3f310d9e37c7f2c042e4
Signed-off-by: Diogo Guerra <dy090.guerra@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Detect missing metric_id before passing through bytearray()

It is possible for a row in Cassandra to have a missing metric_id
(shows as 'null' in cqlsh).  This causes an ugly NoneType error
to be passed up to the user on the command line for
'monaca metric-list'.

Fix is to detect the missing value, log an error, and return the
row with None for the metric_id.

Change-Id: Ie617932c6b12a6cfe441510e120bb77a3470b9cf
Story: 2005305
Task: 30194
(cherry picked from commit d6852ee1b7d548321af104f2a0e4be523a49ed08)

commit_message:
Add support for text ports on Network Policy Spec

This commit adds support for Network Policies that define ports with text
in the ingress or egress section. It checks if the containers
in pods have their ports with the same name as the port defined in the
Network Policy. In the case when the policy is applied over namespace(s),
the pods in that namespace(s) have their containers checked and if matched
a SG rule with a new 'remote_ip_prefixes' pointing to that pod(s) is
created.

Change-Id: I8d4a8b037d7dd48bcec6a549c1cebeb2e71ab96f
Closes-Bug: 1818983

commit_message:
Fix setting of VIP QoS policy

Load balancers were going in to ERROR when updating vip_qos_policy_id in
two different cases:

- QoS extension enabled: the VIP DB data model was incorrectly
  constructed ('vip_qos_policy_id' where it should have been
  'qos_policy_id')
- QoS extension disabled: setting an UUID or None would fail in the LB
  update flow as the extension is disabled, and the API would return
  HTTP 202 to the user.

Conflicts:
    octavia/api/v2/controllers/load_balancer.py
    octavia/tests/unit/api/drivers/amphora_driver/test_amphora_driver.py

commit_message:
Update UPPER_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/stein

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/stein branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: Ie4c0c040e4471648431554448b55cdc6ce2261ab

commit_message:
Modified the completion condition of evacuate

The completion conditions of evacuate are the following.
  - old_vm_state=active, new_vm_state=active
  - old_vm_state=stopped, new_vm_state=stopped
  - old_vm_state=error, new_vm_state=active

"old_vm_state=error, new_vm_state=error" is not completion
of evacuate. So this patch modified this completion condition
of evacuate.

Change-Id: I8ccc857fe0794a49f993fe55c2262a04d0f72ad0
Closes-Bug: #1782516

added_lines: if old_vm_state == 'error': if new_vm_state == 'active': raise loopingcall.LoopingCallDone() else: if old_vm_state == new_vm_state: raise loopingcall.LoopingCallDone()

commit_message:
Add ansible-role-collect-logs project to tripleo

ansible-role-collect-logs is a new tripleo log collection ansible
role seperated from tripleo-quickstart-extras project for reusing
it with other projects.

Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/647667/

Change-Id: I4f2b541b43cb4eadf04778bb93ae97fc3248e5d0

commit_message:
Added install_os_tempest_deps function to install os_tempest deps

In order to isolate the dependencies of os_tempest role,
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/644600/ moves the os_tempest deps
to requirements.yml so that end user can install it easily using
ansible-galaxy and it dumps in  ~/.ansible/roles directory.

https://review.openstack.org/644830 adds the config_template as a
deps under meta/main.yaml so that it will be easily imported.

https://tree.taiga.io/project/tripleo-ci-board/task/896

Change-Id: Ide08c0e78fc496e451af57ca83552db04ff03aea
